habitat_description:
The range of this species includes the Sierra Nevada Mountains of California and extreme west Nevada. Other populations occur in the San Bernardino, San Jacinto, San Gabriel, and Palomar mountains in southern California (Behler and King 1979). Its elevational range in the south is from 365 to 2300 meters, while in the north ranges from 1800 to 3600 meters (Behler and King 1979).
Habitat includes sunny banks and undisturbed lakes and ponds that are typically characterized with sloping gravel banks. Breeding in the lower altitudes occurs from March to May and June to August in higher elevations (Behler and King 1979). Adults are observed on rocks with no surrounding vegetation in the Sierra Nevada Range, while in California they occupy narrow rock-walled canyons and streams in the chaparral area (Lannoo 2005).Populations in southern California are almost exclusive to streams possibly due to lack of lakes in the region (Stebbins 1951).
